INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '80cb57b8-451a-49cf-b95b-f534d4f394e3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum + SQLx — Killing N+1 Queries Before They Kill Your Latency$escape$,
  $escape$SQLx is the default choice for axum apps — async-native, and its `query!` macro catches SQL errors at compile time against your actual schema. SeaORM adds entity relationships and lazy loading, but lazy loading is exactly what causes N+1 problems. In axum handlers, an N+1 emerges when you fetch a list and loop to hydrate related data: one query for posts, then one per post for comments. With 100 posts, that's 101 round trips to Postgres.

The fix with SQLx is a batched `WHERE post_id = ANY($1)` query using Postgres's array operator — a single round trip regardless of list size. Group the results in Rust using a `HashMap`. Avoid SeaORM's `find_related()` inside handler loops for the same reason.

For migrations, embed `sqlx::migrate!()` in your axum startup before `Router::new()` to auto-apply pending migrations from the `migrations/` folder on boot. Pair with `sqlx-cli` (`sqlx migrate add`) for local dev.

Batch at the query layer. Group at the application layer. Never lazy-load in a loop.$escape$,
  $escape$async fn posts_handler(State(pool): State<PgPool>) -> Result<Json<Value>, AppError> {
    let posts = sqlx::query!("SELECT id, title FROM posts")
        .fetch_all(&pool).await?;

    let ids: Vec<i32> = posts.iter().map(|r| r.id).collect();

    // ONE query instead of N — Postgres array operator
    let comments = sqlx::query!(
        "SELECT post_id, body FROM comments WHERE post_id = ANY($1)",
        &ids as &[i32]
    )
    .fetch_all(&pool).await?;

    let mut grouped: HashMap<i32, Vec<String>> = HashMap::new();
    for c in comments { grouped.entry(c.post_id).or_default().push(c.body); }
    Ok(Json(json!(posts.iter().map(|p| json!({"id": p.id, "comments": grouped.get(&p.id)})).collect::<Vec<_>>())))
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
