INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8bbad8f2-74dd-4952-8d29-cc7885ad529d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum JWT Auth — Typed Extractors Over Middleware$escape$,
  $escape$axum's idiomatic auth pattern uses `FromRequestParts` to build a typed extractor that rejects unauthenticated requests before they reach your handlers. Define a `Claims` struct, implement `FromRequestParts<S>` for it, and axum invokes it automatically when a handler declares it as a parameter — no separate middleware layer needed for basic JWT validation.

Inside `from_request_parts`, pull the `Authorization` header, strip the `Bearer ` prefix, then validate with `jsonwebtoken::decode`. Return `StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED` on any failure; return the decoded `Claims` on success. The handler receives a verified value — no `Option` unwrapping, no extension tower, no threading state manually through layers.

For route-scoped cross-cutting concerns (JWKS cache refresh, per-user rate limiting), use `Router::layer(middleware::from_fn_with_state(state.clone(), auth_fn))`. Scope layers tightly to specific `Router` groups, not the root — public routes like `/health` and webhook endpoints won't be gated. The extractor pattern owns per-handler auth; `layer` owns group-level concerns. Mixing both gives you fine-grained control without polluting every handler signature.$escape$,
  $escape$use axum::{async_trait, extract::FromRequestParts, http::{request::Parts, StatusCode}};
use jsonwebtoken::{decode, DecodingKey, Validation};
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct Claims { pub sub: String, pub exp: usize }

#[async_trait]
impl<S: Send + Sync> FromRequestParts<S> for Claims {
    type Rejection = StatusCode;

    async fn from_request_parts(parts: &mut Parts, _state: &S) -> Result<Self, Self::Rejection> {
        let token = parts.headers
            .get("Authorization")
            .and_then(|v| v.to_str().ok())
            .and_then(|s| s.strip_prefix("Bearer "))
            .ok_or(StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED)?;

        decode::<Claims>(token, &DecodingKey::from_secret(b"secret"), &Validation::default())
            .map(|d| d.claims)
            .map_err(|_| StatusCode::UNAUTHORIZED)
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
