INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5726eb90-0e61-43a8-a91a-52f79f1bcade',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Testing — Unit Handlers, Router Integration, and DB Isolation$escape$,
  $escape$axum's architecture makes testing unusually clean. Handler functions are plain async fns — unit test them directly by passing `State(...)`, `Json(...)`, and `Path(...)` extractors without spinning up a server.

For integration tests, convert your `Router` into a `tower::Service` and call `.oneshot(Request)` — no TCP, no port binding. This tests your full middleware stack, extractors, and response serialization in-process. Use `axum::body::to_bytes` to read the response body.

For external HTTP dependencies (e.g. calling GitHub API), use `wiremock::MockServer` — it binds a real local port, returns stubbed responses, and asserts expectations. Pass the base URL through `State` so tests can inject the mock URL.

For database isolation, reach for `sqlx::test` — it spins up a fresh migrated database per test function using a pool fixture, then tears it down automatically. Pair this with a `TestApp` helper struct that holds your `Router` and `PgPool` together, keeping test setup DRY across your test modules.$escape$,
  $escape$// integration test using Router::oneshot()
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_get_user_returns_200() {
    let pool = test_pool().await; // sqlx::test-managed pool
    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/users/:id", get(get_user_handler))
        .with_state(AppState { db: pool });

    let req = Request::builder()
        .uri("/users/42")
        .body(Body::empty())
        .unwrap();

    let res = app.oneshot(req).await.unwrap();
    assert_eq!(res.status(), StatusCode::OK);
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
