INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f59d6f2c-2768-4ab6-9d42-0632c41075d2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$axum Serialization — DTOs, camelCase vs snake_case, and Null Handling$escape$,
  $escape$axum delegates serialization entirely to serde, so your DTO shape is defined at compile time via derive macros. By default, struct field names are serialized as-is (snake_case). To emit camelCase for a JSON API consumed by JavaScript clients, use `#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]` on the struct — no runtime overhead, no middleware needed.

For null handling, axum's `Json<T>` extractor will reject requests where a required field is missing. Wrap optional fields with `Option<T>` and annotate with `#[serde(skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")]` to omit nulls from responses instead of serializing them as `null`. To accept missing fields as `None` during deserialization, add `#[serde(default)]`.

Response DTOs returned via `Json(payload)` are serialized automatically — no `.to_json()` call needed. For asymmetric shapes (accept snake_case, emit camelCase), define separate request and response structs rather than fighting serde with multiple attributes on one type. This keeps handler signatures honest and avoids surprises at the boundary.$escape$,
  $escape$use axum::{Json, routing::post, Router};
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

#[derive(Deserialize)]
#[serde(rename_all = "snake_case")]
struct CreateUserRequest {
    display_name: String,
    #[serde(default)]
    avatar_url: Option<String>,
}

#[derive(Serialize)]
#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]
struct UserResponse {
    user_id: String,
    display_name: String,
    #[serde(skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")]
    avatar_url: Option<String>,
}

async fn create_user(Json(req): Json<CreateUserRequest>) -> Json<UserResponse> {
    Json(UserResponse {
        user_id: "usr_01".into(),
        display_name: req.display_name,
        avatar_url: req.avatar_url,
    })
}$escape$,
  $escape$rust$escape$,
